          "body": "Psalm 20 does not exhaust its meaning in David's battlefield. The New Testament's consistent application of Davidic royal psalms to Jesus opens a Messianic reading that the early church inhabited naturally. The 'mashiach' whom the Lord saves (v. 6) is David historically, but the Psalter's own trajectory (Psalms 2, 22, 45, 110) points to a king whose anointing and crisis surpass David's. Jesus's cry of dereliction (Psalm 22) and His resurrection are the ultimate fulfillment of the pattern: the Anointed One entered the deepest 'day of trouble,' the community's intercession was silent at the cross, and God answered from His holy heaven with the saving strength of His right hand — raising the crucified Mashiach and seating Him at the right hand of power (Psalm 110:1; Acts 2:33-36). The church now prays Psalm 20 not only for earthly leaders but in light of the victory already secured by the risen King. 'Now I know that the Lord saves His anointed' is the church's post-resurrection certainty, not merely its pre-battle hope."
