        "number": 2,
        "title": "'Now I know' — prayer breaks through into certainty",
        "range": "20:6",
        "excerpt": "Now I know that the Lord saves His anointed; He will answer him from His holy heaven with the saving strength of His right hand.",
        "body": "Verse 6 is the psalm's pivot and its theological summit. After five verses of petitionary prayer, a solitary voice — the poet himself, a priest, or a cultic prophet — steps forward and declares confident knowledge: 'Now I know that the Lord saves His anointed.' The Hebrew 'attah' (now) is a temporal hinge — something has shifted. The jussive petitions ('may He...') give way entirely to an indicative declaration ('He will answer him'). The register of the psalm changes from supplication to certainty.\n\nThe source of this certainty has generated considerable discussion. Derek Kidner (Psalms 1-72, TOTC) suggests the verse reflects a prophetic oracle received in the context of worship — a word spoken through an authorized spokesperson that God will save. This would parallel the role of the cult prophet in 2 Chronicles 20:14-17, where in the midst of crisis and prayer, the Spirit of the Lord falls on Jahaziel and he declares 'Do not fear.' Whatever the specific mechanism, the structural effect is clear: prayer, genuinely offered, produces assurance — not because the circumstances have changed, but because faith has seen what God has committed Himself to do.\n\nThe 'right hand' (yamin) is the ancient seat of power, the sword hand, the hand with which a king acts decisively. The psalmist attributes the decisive military action not to the Davidic king's right hand but to God's. This is the psalm's anti-militarism in its starkest form: the battle is the Lord's, the right hand that wins it is His, and the king's anointing means precisely that God has bound Himself to fight for him. The combination of 'holy heaven' (the transcendent throne room) and 'right hand' (immanent decisive action) is the same pairing that characterizes Israel's Exodus theology — the God who is above all is the God who acts within history (Exodus 15:6: 'Your right hand, O Lord, is majestic in power').\n\nThe Christological weight of mashiach (anointed) in v. 6 cannot be overstated in canonical reading. The New Testament explicitly reads the anointed of the Davidic psalms as pointing to Jesus (Acts 4:26 quotes Psalm 2:2; Acts 2:36 declares 'God has made Him both Lord and Christ'). The verse becomes, in its fullest sense, the Father's declaration about the Son — the One who entered the deepest day of trouble (the cross) and whom God answered from His holy heaven with resurrection power.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Attah* (now, v.6) — a temporal pivot marking the shift from petition to certainty; used similarly in Exodus 18:11 and Psalm 119:6 to signal a decisive moment of knowing. *Mashiach* (anointed) — from the verb mashach, to smear or anoint with oil. In the OT it designates kings (1 Samuel 12:3), priests (Leviticus 4:3), and occasionally prophets (1 Kings 19:16). *Gevurah* (saving strength/power, v.6) — might, heroic strength; used of God's mighty acts throughout the Psalter (Psalm 54:1; 71:18)."
