        "title": "Save, O Lord — confident prayer that never goes silent",
        "range": "20:9",
        "excerpt": "Save, O Lord; May the King answer us in the day we call.",
        "body": "The psalm closes with a single verse that is simultaneously a cry, a confession, and a return. After the confident declaration of vv. 7-8, the community does not fall silent in self-assured triumph. They cry out again — 'Save, O Lord.' This is the psalm's final and perhaps most important pastoral instruction: the community that has confessed 'we will boast in the name of the Lord' immediately returns to urgent petition. Confident faith and urgent prayer are not alternatives in Israel's worship; they are simultaneous postures.\n\nThe identity of 'the King' in v. 9b has divided commentators. The Hebrew can be read two ways: (1) 'May the King [i.e., Yahweh, the divine King] answer us when we call' — reading the verse as a continuation of direct address to God, who throughout the Psalter is called King (Psalm 10:16; 29:10; 95:3; 145:1). (2) 'May the King [i.e., the Davidic king] answer us in the day we call' — reading the verse as the community's prayer that through their king's intercession, God will answer them. Both readings are grammatically available, and the ambiguity may be theologically intentional: the human Davidic king mediates God's answers, and Yahweh is the ultimate King through whom all answers flow. The two levels of kingship collapse into one at the psalm's close.\n\nIn Messianic perspective, the verse achieves its fullest resonance. The greater Son of David — crucified, risen, ascended — now sits at the right hand of power (Psalm 110:1; Hebrews 1:3) and 'ever lives to make intercession' for His people (Hebrews 7:25). When the church prays 'Save, O Lord' on any given day of trouble, it prays through and to the Anointed King who has already passed through the deepest crisis and been answered from the holy heaven with resurrection. The community's cry does not land in an empty throne room; it is heard by the King who knows what a day of trouble costs and who has been answered by the right hand of the Father.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yasah* (save, v.9) — the imperative form of the same root that gave us yeshuah (salvation, v.5) and the name Yeshua/Jesus. *Melekh* (king, v.9) — used throughout the Psalter for both the Davidic human king and Yahweh the divine King; the ambiguity is structural, not accidental. *Yom* (day, v.9) — the same word as v. 1's 'day of trouble,' forming a deliberate bracket: the psalm begins and ends in the day of acute need, with Yahweh as the answer to both."
